		<part id="how">
			<title>How to do Microservices?</title>
			<slide id="microservices-letter">
				<title>Following the Letter</title>
				<ul>
					<li>There are <a href="https://martinfowler.com/bliki/MicroservicePrerequisites.html">three basic Microservice Prerequisites</a>:</li>
					<ul>
						<li><em>Rapid provisioning:</em> Stand up new servers in hours</li>
						<li><em>Basic monitoring:</em> Observe technical and business issues</li>
						<li><em>Rapid application deployment:</em> Quickly deploy services to test and production</li>
					</ul>
					<li>Many automation solution nowadays revolve around containers and related approaches</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Use containers such as <a href="https://www.docker.com/">Docker</a> as development/deployment platform</li>
						<li>Use orchestration such as <a href="https://kubernetes.io/">Kubernetes</a> for managing containers</li>
						<li>Use a service mesh such as <a href="https://istio.io/">Istio</a> for container insight and controls</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="microservices-principle">
				<title>Following the Principle</title>
				<ul>
					<li>The idea and goal of microservices is to <em>decouple implementations</em></li>
					<ul>
						<li>Encapsulate implementations and only allow API interactions between them</li>
						<li><em>Polyglotism</em> allows teams to choose the tools that work for them</li>
						<li><em>Continuous Delivery</em> streamlines the way from development to production</li>
					</ul>
					<li>The microservices principle simply is enterprise IT understanding the Web</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Components communicate through network-level standardized interfaces</li>
						<li>Implementation details are completely invisible to the outside</li>
						<li>Components can be added/scaled/modified/replaced individually and easily</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
